Despite achieving considerable success in accomplishing MDGs [37], South Asian countries continue to suffer from the concerned issues and are globally ranked very low in terms of the Human Development Index (HDI) [38]. After MDGs, the region proactively adopted the more ambitious United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) in 2015. Better accepted as “The 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development” comprises 17 SDGs (as shown in Fig. 3
                     ) and 169 targets evaluated by 234 indicators. Seven of these SDGs are related to energy and environmental sustainability as explained in Table 2
                      in terms of targeted indicators. The first six goals of SDGs were adopted from MDGs and other new goals were introduced for inclusive and sustainable growth, development, clean energy, and climate change and its related impacts.
